Pawe≈Ç Kolarz, Jan Marsza≈Çek, Jaros≈Çaw Ko¬¥zlak, Ma≈Çgorzata Zabi¬¥
AGH University of Science and Technology, Al. Mickiewicza 30, 30-059 Krak¬¥ow, Poland

Abstract
Our goal was to develop an environment which will make it possible to model and optimise supply chains and
company behaviours, as well as to test the inÔ¨Çuence of applying diÔ¨Äerent decision algorithms. The system consists of
a set of companies which cooperate and compete with one another by oÔ¨Äering and buying products and negotiating
their conditions of transactions. Throughout the presented work we focused on the realisation of the parts of the
strategic planner module. Producers tend to maximise proÔ¨Åts, among other ways, by modifying the margin of oÔ¨Äered
products.
The main aim of the applied decision algorithm is to have a feature of adapting to a given situation: to select the
best model of the simulation world and to choose the most adequate actions in the given situations. The Ô¨Årst aspect is
addressed by the use of an adaptive algorithm which chooses the best demand prediction algorithm in a given situation.
The second aspect is addressed by the clustering technique which identiÔ¨Åes the similar situations on the market as one
possible state and assigns with it the most proÔ¨Åtable action.
Keywords: multi‚Äìagent systems, company modelling, clustering, prediction

1. Introduction
The problem of building a beneÔ¨Åcial supply chain of management is nowadays of signiÔ¨Åcant importance.
A supply chain [1] is made up of enterprises (suppliers, focal company, customer) linked together by Ô¨Çows of
products, services, information and Ô¨Ånancial means, which may include production.
As long as useful decisions concerning the setting of market strategies and choice of suppliers and clients are
performed by humans, the design of an automatic model of these activities still may potentially oÔ¨Äer numerous
advantages.
Firstly, there are domains, where the automatic setting of the supply chain and market strategies could be useful,
especially in cases of activities concerning virtual goods and services in the Internet, where the response time is an
important factor.
Secondly, a development of a system where the setting of supply chains is automatic may make it possible to
analyse the behaviour of diÔ¨Äerent market settings and to evaluate strategies of activities.
