Our goal was to develop an environment which will make it possible to model and optimise supply chains and
company behaviours, as well as to test the inÔ¨Çuence of the application of diÔ¨Äerent decision algorithms.
The way of achieving it was to apply the decision algorithm with features of adapting to a given situation, to select
the best model of the simulation world and to choose the most adequate actions in the given situations. We particularly
focused on the problems of the choice of the best prediction of demand for products for the given market conditions
and on the choice of the best price margin to win the competition on the market.
The Ô¨Årst aspect is addressed by the use of an adaptive algorithm which chooses the best demand prediction algorithm in a given situation.
The important element of the enterprise decision strategy is to guarantee the best level of the stocks, which depends, to a large degree, on the predicted values of orders for the next n simulation steps. The nearer the predicted
value is to the real value, the more precisely the warehouse is able to plan deliveries, and is able, in eÔ¨Äect, to guarantee that at the end of each step of the simulation only the minimum amount of goods (safety buÔ¨Äer) remains in the
warehouse. Incorrect predictions of demand (inÔ¨Çatedness of demand) increases storage costs and an underestimation
may cause a lack of components in the warehouse and to subsequent production standstills.
The second aspect is addressed either by the predeÔ¨Åned (according to experiences) set of rules or by the clustering
technique which identiÔ¨Åes the similar situations on the market as one possible state and assigns with it the most
proÔ¨Åtable action.
2. Related research and useful information
The multi‚Äìagent approach is often used for modelling and the optimisation of supply chains. In [2] a concept
of a multi‚Äìagent environment is presented which consists of diÔ¨Äerent components necessary for the composition of
supply‚Äìchains, and may be used for analysis of the results of the choice of strategies of company activities. In [3] an
overview is given for diÔ¨Äerent problems associated with supply chains which were solved with the use of agents as
well as a classiÔ¨Åcation of methods used by agents.
An important aspect of the decision making of agents in supply chains is their way of leading negotiations and
the choice of negotiation strategies. In [4] an overview of methods of negotiation modelling (based on game theory,
heuristics, argumentation) is given while a classiÔ¨Åcation of negotiation schemas concerning the electronic markets
may be found in [5].
Another important question associated with the modern supply chains is their feature associated with the adaptation to the given situation. The analysis of robust or Ô¨Çexible solutions for selected strategies of behaviour is done in
[6].
One of the most important elements of adequate decision making is the use of suitable prediction techniques.
In [7] the use of prediction by agents, which participate in the tournament of agents building the most economic
supply chains ‚Äì Trading Agent Competition (TAC) [8], is described. For the analysis of the current situation and
prediction of future states, techniques of data mining and machine learning are used. For example in [9] association
rules, clustering and decision trees are used, and in [10] ‚Äì Markov correction prediction process and Gausian mixture
models are applied.
In our opinion, the main diÔ¨Äerence between models of the companies and market used by TAC and our model is
that, we take into consideration diÔ¨Äerent kinds of contracts (short‚Äìterm and long‚Äìterm) in the model.
3. System model
The goal of the work was to design and implement an environment which makes it possible to model diÔ¨Äerent
states of the market and to analyse results of the diÔ¨Äerent strategies used by companies on the market.
3.1. Market environment
The market environment consists of the following types of agents: companies, clients and negotiators. Based on
input components obtained from other companies‚Äìsuppliers, the company manufactures Ô¨Ånal products and delivers
them to customers or other companies. The customers declare demands for Ô¨Ånal products, which leads to assigning
contracts with appropriate companies. Contracts are described by the following parameters: the kind of product,

Pawe? Kolarz et al. / Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1533 ‚Äì 1542

1535

number of entities, the price and the time of delivery (usually the shorter time of delivery causes the higher expected
and accepted price).
The task of the negotiators is to gather oÔ¨Äers of accepted contracts submitted by companies and customers, coupling contracts that Ô¨Åt together and to determine the conditions acceptable for the parties concerned. The separate
realisation of the module which represents negotiators that resolve the negotiations between agents makes it possible
to change the negotiation model relatively easily, without the necessity of changing remaining decision elements.
In the framework of the works done so far, two diÔ¨Äerent negotiation models of the market subjects were implemented. In the current work, a model for determining price and assigning the partners, based on laws of supply and
demand, is used. In [11], another model which takes into consideration the market strength of the given parties is
used.
3.2. Model of agent‚Äìcompany
The main subject of the research having the most complex decision elements is the agent representing a company.
Its knowledge consists of: (i) quantities of sold elements of the given product in the previous and current simulation
steps and a global demand for a given product in the previous and current steps as well as (ii) the level of the current
stocks and estimated time of delivery of the product to the client.
The activities of the company are handled by the following behaviours, which group together logically linked
actions: (i) participation in the negotiation for selling products; (ii) production and sending sold products to costumers;
(iii) optimisation of the production strategy and update of the delivered oÔ¨Äer; (iv) sending information about the
readiness to pass subsequent steps of the simulation; (v) receiving information about the start of a new step in the
simulation.
The agent company consists of the following functional modules (Fig. 1):
‚Ä¢ a buyer ‚Äì responsible for buying components for production,
‚Ä¢ a seller ‚Äì responsible for selling Ô¨Ånal products and determination conditions of selling,
‚Ä¢ a warehouse manager ‚Äì responsible for determination needs of buying to fulÔ¨Ål the stocks levels and to bear
stock maintenance costs,
‚Ä¢ a production module ‚Äì produces Ô¨Ånal products from input components,
‚Ä¢ a strategy manager ‚Äì responsible for choice of decision strategies and conÔ¨Åguration of activities of other modules.
3.3. Strategic manager module ‚Äì version I
The goal of the work is to identify the best possible strategies of activities of the company for the given conditions.
To achieve this goal, we have so far applied techniques of reinforcement learning (such as q‚Äìlearning algorithm [12])
or diÔ¨Äerent demand level prediction algorithms, rule based and clustering algorithm (last three presented in this paper).
The StrategyManager (S tratMan) module may be described as follows:
S tratMan = (conds, preds, strats)

(1)

where conditions conds represent the current state of the company and its environment, preds represent the predicted
evaluation of elements describing conditions and strats represent possible decision activities.
Condition conds consists of the following elements:
‚Ä¢ a state of the company ‚Äì Ô¨Ånancial means, established contracts and conditions;
‚Ä¢ customer behaviour ‚Äì described by a character of the demand for Ô¨Ånal products and requirements concerning
the prices and the delivery time;
‚Ä¢ competitor behaviour ‚Äì the percent of shares of the market owned by the company;

