A concept of module functioning is shown in Fig. 2. IdentiÔ¨Åcation of the market situation (MS) is done based
on the state of the enterprise and its knowledge of the market (resulting from history and prediction). Values of the
description of the situation measures which are described below (SMS) are computed. They make the foundation of the
current market situation MS. For given market situations, evaluation of results of appropriate strategies performance
from the set SS is done; these evaluations are described by the value increase of the appropriate versions of the goal
function after the considered number of steps. On the basis of these values the choice of the most appropriate strategy
for a given enterprise is made.
Situation identiÔ¨Åcation. To evaluate the situation of an enterprise, the following measures (SMS) describing the
current situation are taken into account:
‚Ä¢ Measures characterising the components purchase state (describing the course of action for certain simulation
steps):
‚Äì the contracted time of delivery of the i-th copy of the j-th component ordered in step t;
‚Äì the price of the i-th copy of the j-th component ordered in step t, settled by the contract;
‚Äì the number of the delay rounds of the j-th component ordered in step t;
‚Äì the percentage of type j components ordered by an enterprise in the whole demand for the component in
step t for the considered market;
‚Äì the percentage of type j components received in the whole demand for the component in step t for the
considered market;
‚Ä¢ Measures characterising the state of currently possessed resources:
‚Äì the number of possessed copies of components of j type in step t;
‚Äì for how many steps the number of possessed j-type components is suÔ¨Écient, if they are being sold according to the sale level of the former rounds, taking into consideration enterprise production abilities;
evaluations using diÔ¨Äerent methods of demand prediction are possible;

1538

Pawe? Kolarz et al. / Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1533 ‚Äì 1542

‚Äì for how many steps the number of possessed j-type components is suÔ¨Écient, if they are being sold in
numbers covering the whole demand;
‚Ä¢ Measures characterising the Ô¨Ånal state of product sales:
‚Äì the percentage of the total sale of elements of the Ô¨Ånal product j, which makes the enterprise sale in the
subsequent steps t;
‚Äì the time of delivery of the i-th copy of the j-type Ô¨Ånal product contracted in step t;
‚Äì the margin at sale of the i-th copy of the j-type Ô¨Ånal product ordered in step t;
‚Äì the number of delay rounds at delivery of the copy of the j-type Ô¨Ånal product ordered in the step t.
The characteristics of the strategy: As a result of the strategy choice, the change of values occurs of the decision
attributes responsible for:
‚Ä¢ Actions related to the purchase of the component; they comprise of modiÔ¨Åcation of the number of preferred
purchased components of certain types, transaction conditions depending on the number of components being
bought, proposed and accepted prices and times of delivery
‚Ä¢ Actions related to the sale of elements; they comprise of modiÔ¨Åcation of the number of preferred Ô¨Ånal products
sold, transaction conditions depending on the number of components being bought, proposed and accepted
prices and times of delivery.
‚Ä¢ Actions related to the conclusion of the long-term contract with the enterprise selling components and to conditions of such a contract comprising modiÔ¨Åcation of the accepted price, the accepted number range of elements
concerning the transaction and consequences of the contract break.
‚Ä¢ Actions related to the conclusion of the long-term contract with the enterprise buying Ô¨Ånal products manufactured by the enterprise, comprising of modiÔ¨Åcations of the accepted price, the accepted number range of
elements concerning the transaction and consequences of the contract break.
Evaluation of the results of strategy using in the given states. The evaluation of using a strategy (Eval) may be
done in diÔ¨Äerent ways. Currently we plan to apply machine learning technique, thus carrying out many simulations
and evaluations of choice results of certain strategies by examining the goal function (G) values, after diÔ¨Äerent, given
numbers of simulation steps. The evaluation may be performed with the use of diÔ¨Äerent criteria:
‚Ä¢ The average gained assets in round t after the choice of the given strategy described either using cash only or
considering values of purchased components;
‚Ä¢ The maximal gained assets;
‚Ä¢ The minimal gained assets;
‚Ä¢ The probability of transfer to other simulation patterns and quality evaluation of these subsequent patterns by
using the evaluation
4. Realisation
The system was realised with the use of the agent platform JADE. The scheme of the architecture of the system is
presented in Fig. 3.
In the Ô¨Ågure, the main types of interactions between agents are presented: the sending of initialisation information,
exchange of data about oÔ¨Äers and request realisation and synchronisation of steps.
The additional kinds of agents, necessary for the realisation of the simulation ‚Äì Data Agent and Simulation Agent
are presented. The Data Agent is responsible for storing data about the simulation conÔ¨Åguration and providing them
to the agents as well as for the gathering of data necessary for the visualisation, generation of statistics and rapports.

Pawe? Kolarz et al. / Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1533 ‚Äì 1542

1539

Simulation agents decide on transitions to subsequent simulation steps and phases and informs agents about it.
Every simulation step consists of two phases: (i) negotiation and production phase and (ii) delivery and data actualisation phase. During the phase (i) negotiations, productions, ordering of buying components and realisation of requests
are performed. During the phase (ii) an actualisation of data takes place, concerning prices of products by agents and
the delivery of ordered components and products.

Figure 3: Scheme of the system architecture.

The deÔ¨Åned model of behaviours of agents, makes it possible to implement activities which are executed by the
agent parallelly. The given behaviours are triggered by the arrival of a message or a cyclic time event.
For identiÔ¨Åcation of the situations using clustering techniques, the environment Weka [13, 14] was used.
5. Selected experiments
During the valuation of environment and its components, diÔ¨Äerent experimental scenarios were performed for
diÔ¨Äerent market conditions, and especially, chosen sets of companies and their conÔ¨Ågurations and diÔ¨Äerent characteristics of time distribution of demand for Ô¨Ånal products. Experiments concerning the accuracy of prediction oÔ¨Äered by
diÔ¨Äerent kinds of standard predictors and by an adaptive predictor are described in the next subsection. In the following subsection, the results obtained using rule-based and clustering algorithms for decision making are presented.
5.1. Adaptive Predictor
Analysis of the adaptive predictor conÔ¨Åguration. The aim of research was to Ô¨Åx the possibility to connect many
diÔ¨Äerent algorithms of demand prediction into one adaptive algorithm. It is known that each of them has its own
speciÔ¨Åcity and behaves diÔ¨Äerently for diÔ¨Äerent data. Merging them into one and applying the best one in the very
moment should be advantageous. Adaptive predictor has originated by encapsulating algorithms: Moving average,
Arithmetic average, Holt. Each of these algorithms is fed by the same data and in every simulation step we obtain
the values predicted in such a way. The values are used subsequently to establish prediction quality and to choose the
best algorithm at any moment. To Ô¨Åx the prediction quality we apply a simple measure which consists of summing up
a prediction error of the last n steps. An absolute diÔ¨Äerence between the real and predicted demands is assumed as a
prediction error.
Adaptive prediction is controlled by two parameters. The Ô¨Årst one is a number of steps, after which, cyclically,
the enumeration of quality of predictors and the choice of the best one (period of the choice of prediction - OP) is

1540

Pawe? Kolarz et al. / Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1533 ‚Äì 1542

performed. The second parameter is a number of historical data (the formerly predicted values), which are used to Ô¨Åx
the prediction quality (the value is denoted as H).
The research was done for the following runs of demand for Ô¨Ånal products: (A) ‚Äì single parabola, (B) ‚Äì double
parabola (sinus), (C) ‚Äì double parabola disturbed by a random variable [-2:2], (D) ‚Äì constant increase disturbed by
a random variable [-2:2], (E) ‚Äì constant value disturbed by a random variable [-5:5]. The whole research of demand
comprises 100 steps.
As the research has proved, an adaptive predictor gives the best estimation of the demand for each examined
example. In the table below, the total results are presented. The single prediction algorithms are compared with the
adaptive algorithms. The values mean percentage of the prediction error against the real demand.
