Example of experiments with obtained conÔ¨Åguration. After selecting the best conÔ¨Åguration of the algorithm
for a signiÔ¨Åcant number of cases, the next goal to evaluate was, if the use of the more accurate prediction technique
allows us to obtain a Ô¨Ånal better result expressed by the total incomes of companies and total level of stocks was
applied.
Because of the diÔ¨Äerent factors inÔ¨Çuencing the Ô¨Ånal results, the more accurate prediction did not lead to the better
results in every cases. Especially, when unexpected increasement of the demand took place and the storage costs were

Pawe? Kolarz et al. / Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1533 ‚Äì 1542

1541

relatively low, keeping higher level of stocks was more advantageous then having good overall demand prediction
level.
Its strength was displayed especially for cases where demand had changing and complex characteristics and features of diÔ¨Äerent prediction algorithms were necessary, the importance of predication accuracy also increased when
high storage costs were used. We considered the Ô¨Ånal demand in the form of a step function with constant lengths of
intervals, and two alternatively changing values. The total incomes obtained by companies using diÔ¨Äerent prediction
algorithms were as follows: adaptive: 265888151, Holtz: 224417881 (16 % worse than using the adaptive), moving
average: 256302250 (4 % worse than using the adaptive), arithmetic: 257172944 (4 % worse than using the adaptive).
The adaptive algorithm quickly emerges after the real demand, which allows the warehouse to better adjust to the
given situation.
5.2. Situation identiÔ¨Åcation using rule-based algorithm and clustering techniques
Two solutions presented in sections 3.3 and 3.4 were compared: using empiric decision rules or by using clustering
techniques for the identiÔ¨Åcation of the situation.
The rules concerned decision about the setting of price margin for selling products, conditions oÔ¨Äered for buying
components and the level of the stocks.
For the identiÔ¨Åcation of the situation in the performed tests we used simpliÔ¨Åed, in regard to the one described in
section 3.4, set of measures describing the situation. For the analysis of the results and the construction of the clusters
in the performed tests following data about company was taken into consideration: total capital increase, gross and
net income increase, outcome increase, warehouse costs increase.
For the given product and producer the following data was considered: global demand increase, global market
share of the producer for the given product, global gross income increase, margin increase, mean delivery time, part
in global sale, price increase, used production capacity increase,
In subsequent steps decisions were evaluated according to income of gain obtained in the subsequent steps.
